#Text=Vernon County Jane Doe
#Text=Vernon County Jane
#Text=Doe
#Text=is an American murder victim whose body was found on May 4 , 1984 .
#Text=Her identity remains unknown . [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=Her hands had been removed , probably to prevent identification by means of fingerprinting .
#Text=The case has been heavily investigated since discovery of the body , with no progress toward finding either her identity or her murderer . [ 4 ]
#Text=Discovery of the body
#Text=The body was found on the night of May 4 , 1984 , near the town of Westby , Wisconsin at 11:15 . [ 4 ]
#Text=It was found by three teenagers within 24 to 48 hours after her death . [ 5 ] [ 6 ]
#Text=There was extensive damage to the victim 's head , which left her face unrecognizable until mortuary procedures were conducted . [ 7 ]
#Text=After the case was broadcast on the news , a couple stated that they had seen a suspicious man near the location .
#Text=He was returning to the driver 's seat of a yellow car , believed to be a 1982 Datsun . [ 8 ]
#Text=When police went to the spot , they found tire tracks from a hasty U-turn .
#Text=A broken denture , blood , and a man 's watch were also found there . [ 1 ]
#Text=Because of this evidence , it is believed that she was killed at another location alongside the same road , and that her body was then taken to the location where she was found . [ 9 ]
#Text=The victim had been murdered , as she suffered blunt force injury to her head , which had broken her jaw , an eye socket and the pair of dentures that she was wearing .
#Text=There was also sharp-force trauma to the left side of the head , near the ear . [ 7 ]
#Text=Her hands had been removed , most likely to prevent identification through fingerprint matching . [ 1 ] [ 3 ] [ 10 ]
#Text=Description and clothing
#Text=Vernon County Jane Doe was a white woman between 50 and 65 years old .
#Text=She had graying brown hair , presumed to have been done in a perm .
#Text=She was 5 feet 5 to 5 feet 6 inches ( approximately 170cm ) .
#Text=She did not appear to have any unique physical features . [ 4 ]
#Text=She weighed 150 pounds ( 68kg ) and had worn dentures , probably those that were found with her body . [ 6 ]
#Text=The dentures , missing two teeth , had both raised and indented numbers upon them , believed to be serial numbers .
#Text=Despite this , investigators have stated that serial numbers for the given product were not assigned to specific recipients , which would not yield clues to the victim 's identity . [ 7 ]
#Text=She was wearing a multicolored coat , a black dress decorated with a blue-and-white paisley print , a blue turtleneck sweater , and nylon stockings .
#Text=The brand labels of the clothing had been removed . [ 3 ] [ 11 ]
#Text=There were distinctive buttons on her clothes ; these had unique stitching . [ 12 ]
#Text=Investigation

#Text=Over 4,000 leads have surfaced in the case , one recently being the arrest of multiple persons who fraudulently used checks from a missing Amherst , Wisconsin woman who disappeared around the same time as when the Jane Doe was found . [ 13 ] [ 14 ]
#Text=Despite the possible link to Amherst , police believe that she did not reside in the area where she was found . [ 11 ]
#Text=Seven missing women have been ruled out as possible identities . [ 2 ] [ 15 ]
#Text=Authorities have used news media multiple times toward identifying the victim .
#Text=In 2012 , officials " pushed " the case to reach areas of both Minnesota and Wisconsin that were linked to Highway 14 . [ 4 ]
#Text=The case was broadcast in a three-day news special , titled as " Catching Her Killer : Justice for Jane Doe , " to uncover new leads in 2013 .
#Text=Yet no lead so far has proved useful . [ 5 ]
#Text=She was interred in the Viroqua cemetery . Her headstone bears the words " Jane Doe " and the date of the discovery of her body . [ 5 ]
#Text=On August 12 , 2015 , her body was exhumed and sent to the crime lab in Madison , Wisconsin , for testing in hopes of identifying her .
#Text=The body was returned and buried the next day .
#Text=DNA
#Text=was also harvested and began processing at the University of North Texas .

#Text=A new forensic facial reconstruction of the victim was released in December 2015 by a University in Arizona that created the likeness based on physical characteristics of the woman 's skull . [ 4 ]
#Text=The rendering was completed by forensic artist Catyana Falsetti , whose husband was also working on the case at the University . [ 7 ]
#Text=Forensic testing on the pollen present on the victim 's clothing in 2018 indicated she may have originated from Arizona or New Mexico . [ 16 ]
#Text=Authorities would later seek assistance from the DNA Doe Project in hopes to identify the victim . [ 17 ]
